Flow:
HTTP request → Controller (@RestController) → Service (@Service) → Repository (JpaRepository) → Database

Postman (HTTP request)
  → Controller (@RestController) — receives request, calls service
  → Service (@Service) — business logic, calls repository
  → Repository (JpaRepository interface) — Spring auto-generates SQL
  → Hibernate — translates to actual SQL
  → H2 Database — stores/retrieves rows


Controller->Maps which http request goes to which service
Service-> does findAll, save kinds of operations
Repository-> interface(not class) which extends JpaRepository<the entity this repository manages, type of entity's @Id field>

Model: outline of Database, has entities @Entity, has getter and setters and constructor as fields are defined here.
@Entity: Marks a class as a DB table

super(): Calls parent constructor from subclass

the foreign key always lives on the "many" side

In ClassRoomService::
Optional<Faculty> and .orElseThrow(...).  // We don't explicitly use Optional<>; its abstraction
findById() doesn't return a Faculty directly — it returns an Optional<Faculty>, because the ID you searched for might not exist in the database.

 @PathVariables — values embedded directly in the URL path itself.
 Difference Between::
 @RequestBody - pulls entire Json; like Faculty faculty :: pulls all fields
 @RequestParam — pulls values from the query string (?className=Math101&facultyId=2). Good for optional or simple flat parameters.
 @PathVariable — pulls values embedded directly in the URL path (/classrooms/1/enroll/3). Good for identifying a specific resource
 (REST convention: the URL itself represents "what" you're acting on).



 bidirectional JSON serialization loop:: When ManytoMany Classroom->Faculty->Classroom... so on infinite when they call each other while posting and adding fields
 Solve easy fix can be @JsonIgnore in any one so that Jackson only follows one relationship


Also check Desktop file for microservices

What is unit testing?
A unit test tests one class in isolation — specifically its logic —
without involving the database, the web server, Spring, or any other real dependencies.
The key word is isolation. Our StudentService depends on StudentRepository
In a unit test we don't want to actually hit the database —
we want to test only the logic inside StudentService itself.

Two tools we have used
JUnit 5 — the testing framework. Gives us @Test, assertEquals, assertNotNull etc.

General Unit Test Pattern: AAA pattern
// 1. ARRANGE — set up your data and tell mocks what to return
// 2. ACT — call the actual method you're testing
// 3. ASSERT — verify the result is what you expected

COMPLETE PROJECT OVERVIEW::

classmanager/
├── model/
│   ├── Person.java          (abstract, @Entity, @Inheritance JOINED)
│   ├── Student.java         (extends Person, @ManyToMany ClassRoom)
│   ├── Faculty.java         (extends Person, @OneToMany ClassRoom)
│   ├── ClassRoom.java       (@ManyToOne Faculty, @ManyToMany Students)
│   ├── Assignment.java      (@ManyToOne ClassRoom)
│   └── Submission.java      (@ManyToOne Assignment + Student, isLate())
├── repository/
│   ├── StudentRepository
│   ├── FacultyRepository
│   ├── ClassRoomRepository
│   ├── AssignmentRepository (findByClassRoomId — derived query)
│   └── SubmissionRepository (findByAssignmentId — derived query)
├── service/
│   ├── StudentService
│   ├── FacultyService
│   ├── ClassRoomService
│   ├── AssignmentService
│   └── SubmissionService    (getStudentsWhoSubmitted, getStudentsWhoDidNotSubmit — Streams)
└── controller/
    ├── StudentController
    ├── FacultyController
    ├── ClassRoomController
    ├── AssignmentController
    └── SubmissionController



    @Configuration   → marks a class as a manual bean factory
    @Bean            → marks a method whose return value becomes a Spring bean
    @Component       → marks YOUR class for auto-detection by component scan
    @Service         → @Component + semantic meaning (business logic layer)
    @Repository      → @Component + semantic meaning (data layer) + exception translation
    @RestController  → @Component + @ResponseBody (web layer)